    "metadata": {
      "kernelspec": {
        "display_name": "Jupyter Notebook",
        "name": "jupyter"
      }
    },
    "nbformat_minor": 5,
    "nbformat": 4,
    "cells": [
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "# Welcome to Snowflake Notebooks in Workspaces! \u{1F31F}\\n\\nSnowflake Notebooks are fully-managed Jupyter-powered notebook built for end-to-end DS and ML development on Snowflake data. \\n\\nThis includes: \\n- \u{1F40D} **Familiar Jupyter experience** - Directly connected to the governed Snowflake data. \\n- \u{1F4BB} **Inside Snowflake Workspaces** - Organize and run notebooks alongside your other files.\\n- \u{1F9E0} **Powerful for AI/ML** - Runs in our pre-built Container Runtime (CPU or GPU) with popular DS/ML packages pre-installed.\\n- \u{1F3DB}\u{FE0F} **Governed collaboration** - Enable multiple users to collaborate via Git-backed Workspaces or Shared Workspaces."
        },
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "## 1. Connect and run the notebook\\n\\nPress [Run all] or [Connect] to create and connect your notebook to a service"
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "## 2. Create some customer data\\n\\nThis query generates a random table of customer data to explore"
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "code",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "source": "%%sql -r dataframe_1\\nselect\\n  seq4() as customer_id,\\n  'customer_' || (customer_id + 1) as name,\\n  'customer_' || (customer_id + 1) || '@example.com' as email,\\n  dateadd(day, -uniform(0, 3650, random()), current_date()) as signup_date,\\n  round(uniform(100, 100000, random()) / 100, 2) as lifetime_value\\nfrom table(generator(rowcount => 1000));",
        "execution_count": null,
        "outputs": []
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "## 3. Find high value customers\\n\\nThis will show customers worth $800 or more. As you'll see, we're referencing the dataframe created above."
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "code",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "source": "%%sql -r dataframe_2\\nSELECT * FROM {{dataframe_1}} WHERE \\"LIFETIME_VALUE\\" > 800;",
        "execution_count": null,
        "outputs": []
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "## 4. Visualize customer tenure vs spend\\n\\nView the chart to see the distribution of customer tenture vs spend. Again, we're using the dataframe that was generated above."
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "code",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "source": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\nimport pandas as pd\\n\\ndataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(dataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE'])\\ndataframe_1['days_since_signup'] = (pd.Timestamp.today() - dataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE']).dt.days\\ndataframe_1 = dataframe_1.sort_values('days_since_signup')\\n\\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\\nplt.scatter(dataframe_1['days_since_signup'], dataframe_1['LIFETIME_VALUE'], alpha=0.3)\\nplt.plot(dataframe_1['days_since_signup'], dataframe_1['LIFETIME_VALUE'].rolling(100).mean(), color='red', linewidth=2, label='Rolling Avg')\\n\\nplt.xlabel(\\"Days Since Signup\\")\\nplt.ylabel(\\"Lifetime Value\\")\\nplt.title(\\"Customer Tenure vs Spend\\")\\nplt.legend()\\nplt.show()",
        "execution_count": null,
        "outputs": []
      },
      {
        "cell_type": "markdown",
        "id": "${eU.Z()}",
        "metadata": {},
        "source": "# Congrats! Now create your own! \u{2705}\\nClick \\"Create file\\" in a workspace and select Notebooks.\\n\\n**Resources to help you get started**\\n- [ML Quickstart using GPUs](${r}) - just download the .ipynb and upload to your Workspace!\\n- [Documentation](${t})"
      }
    ]
  }`};function enF(){let e=(0,m.BH)(rc.BY),{logEvent:t,logError:r}=(0,S.f1)(),{getDocsUrl:n}=(0,C.Ve)(),{getWwwSnowflakeUrl:s}=(0,enB.D)(),a={label:(0,C.WI)({id:"NEW"}),title:(0,C.WI)({id:"Notebooks are now in Workspaces!"}),description:(0,C.WI)({id:"Create SQL and Python notebooks alongside your other files, running on our next-gen Container Runtime"})},i=()=>{c(),e({baseName:"notebook_demo",fileExtension:".ipynb",content:enU({docsUrl:n(o2.d$),mlQuickstartUrl:s(o2.sY)}),shouldAwaitCreate:!0}).then(()=>{(0,li.s8)({prompt:o2.Wc,source:"vnext-notebook-onboarding",autoSubmit:!0,forceNewThread:!0})}).catch(e=>{r(e instanceof Error?e:Error(String(e)),"vnext-notebook-onboarding-creation-failed")})},{tour:o,showTour:l,hideTour:c}=(0,ln.O)({popoverId:o2.h,content:a,actionButton:{label:(0,C.WI)({id:"Create a Notebook"}),onClick:()=>{i(),t("notebook-vnext-onboarding.create-clicked")}},placement:"left",keyMap:o2.rd.vNextNotebooks,completedKey:tC.zu});return(0,m.q9)(()=>{let e=setTimeout(()=>{l()},2e3);return()=>clearTimeout(e)}),o}function enz(){let[e,t]=(0,f.useState)(!1),{set:r}=(0,ru.lk)(rI.ql),n=[{popoverId:o2.h,content:{header:(0,C.WI)({id:"Semantic view is available in workspace"}),body:(0,l.jsx)("span",{children:(0,C.WI)({id:"You can create a local semantic view inside workspace and later deploy it to database and schema."})})},align:"right"},{popoverId:o2.h,content:{header:(0,C.WI)({id:"Agent is available in workspace"}),body:(0,l.jsx)("span",{children:(0,C.WI)({id:"You can create a local agent inside workspace and later deploy it to database and schema."})})},align:"right"}],{popover:s,showOnboardingPopover:a}=(0,o5.M)({steps:n,label:(0,C.WI)({id:"New"}),keyMap:o2.rd.agentStudioOnboarding,completedKey:tC.ir,onComplete:()=>{r(!0)}});return((0,oQ.j)(`[data-popover-id="${o2.h}"]`,e=>{e&&(t(!0),a())}),e)?s:null}enF.displayName="VNextNotebookOnboardingTour",enz.displayName="AgentStudioOnboardingPopover";var enH=r(568813);let enV=e=>{let{docsUrl:t,mlQuickstartUrl:r}=e;return JSON.stringify({cells:[{cell_type:"markdown",id:(0,eU.Z)(),metadata:{codeCollapsed:!0,collapsed:!1,name:"Welcome"},source:"# Welcome to Notebooks \uD83D\uDCD4\n\nThis notebook shows how you can:\n- Query data with SQL\n- Switch seamlessly to Python\n- Use Cortex Code to generate analysis and visualizations without writing code\n\nTry running each cell step by step \uD83D\uDC47"},{cell_type:"code",execution_count:null,id:(0,eU.Z)(),metadata:{codeCollapsed:!1,language:"sql",name:"Sample query: top customers by revenue",resultVariableName:"dataframe_1",title:"Sample query: top customers by revenue"},outputs:[],source:"%%sql -r dataframe_1\nselect\n  seq4() as customer_id,\n  'customer_' || (customer_id + 1) as name,\n  'customer_' || (customer_id + 1) || '@example.com' as email,\n  dateadd(day, -uniform(0, 3650, random()), current_date()) as signup_date,\n  round(uniform(100, 100000, random()) / 100, 2) as lifetime_value\nfrom table(generator(rowcount => 1000));"},{cell_type:"code",execution_count:null,id:(0,eU.Z)(),metadata:{codeCollapsed:!1,language:"python",name:"Use Python to visualize SQL results",title:"Use Python to visualize SQL results"},outputs:[],source:"# Run the SQL cell above first to populate dataframe_1.\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport pandas as pd\n\ndataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(dataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE'])\ndataframe_1['days_since_signup'] = (pd.Timestamp.today() - dataframe_1['SIGNUP_DATE']).dt.days\ndataframe_1 = dataframe_1.sort_values('days_since_signup')\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\nplt.scatter(dataframe_1['days_since_signup'], dataframe_1['LIFETIME_VALUE'], alpha=0.3)\nplt.plot(dataframe_1['days_since_signup'], dataframe_1['LIFETIME_VALUE'].rolling(100).mean(), color='red', linewidth=2, label='Rolling Avg')\n\nplt.xlabel(\"Days Since Signup\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Lifetime Value\")\nplt.title(\"Customer Tenure vs Spend\")\nplt.legend()\nplt.show()\n"},{cell_type:"markdown",id:(0,eU.Z)(),metadata:{codeCollapsed:!0,collapsed:!1,name:"Next steps with Cortex Code"},source:`# Congrats! Now create your own! ✅

**You can ask Cortex Code to analyze the SQL results without writing code**

Example prompts to try:

1. "Create a bar chart for the SQL cell (or use a specific cell name)"
2. "Identify any outliers and explain why they stand out"
3. "Add a cell for trendline or ranking visualization"
4. "Summarize key insights from this data in plain English and present in a Markdown cell"

Just write your prompt and let Cortex Code generate the Python + visualization!

**Resources to help you get started**
